SIMPLE: glaze
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Glaze
<hw>Glaze</hw> <pr>(gl⟦amac⟧z)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Glazed</conjf> <pr>(gl⟦amac⟧zd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. &
vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Glazing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>glasen</ets>, <ets>glazen</ets>, fr. <ets>glas</ets>. See
<er>Glass</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To furnish (a window, a house, a sash, a case, etc.)
with glass.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Two cabinets daintily paved, richly handed, and <qex>glazed</qex>
with crystalline glass.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To incrust, cover, or overlay with a thin surface,
consisting of, or resembling, glass; <as>as, to <ex>glaze</ex>
earthenware</as>; hence, to render smooth, glasslike, or glossy; <as>as,
to <ex>glaze</ex> paper, gunpowder, and the like</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Sorrow's eye <qex>glazed</qex> with blinding tears.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Paint.)</fld> <def>To apply thinly a transparent or
semitransparent color to (another color), to modify the
effect.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Cookery)</fld> <def>To cover (a donut, cupcake,
meat, etc.) with a thin layer of edible syrup, or other substance which
may solidify to a glossy coating. The material used for glazing is
usually sweet or highly flavored.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Glaze</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Glaze
<hw>Glaze</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To become glazed of
glassy.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Glaze</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Glaze
<hw>Glaze</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The vitreous coating of
pottery or porcelain; anything used as a coating or color in glazing.
See <er>Glaze</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>, 3.</def>
<rj><au>Ure.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Cookery)</fld> <def>Broth reduced by boiling to a
gelatinous paste, and spread thinly over braised dishes.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A glazing oven. See <er>Glost oven</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>glazed</ent>⟦br⟧
